# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: paris
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The **10th arrondissement of Paris** (*Xe arrondissement*) is one of the 20 arrondissements of the capital city of France.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] In spoken French, the arrondissement is referred to as *le dixième* ([dizjɛm]; "the tenth", formally *le dixième arrondissement de Paris*).
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The arrondissement, called Entrepôt (warehouse), is situated on the right bank of the River Seine.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] It contains two of the seven large mainline railway stations of Paris: the Gare du Nord and the Gare de l'Est.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] Built during the 19th century, these two termini are among the busiest in Europe.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The 10th arrondissement also contains a large portion of the Canal Saint-Martin, linking the northeastern parts of Paris with the Seine.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The current mayor of the 10th arrondissement, since 2017, is Alexandra Cordebard.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The land area of the arrondissement is 2.892 km2 (1.117 sq mi; 715 acres).
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The 10th arrondissement is often referred to as *l'Entrepôt*.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] The peak population of the 10th arrondissement occurred in 1881, when it had 162,671 inhabitants.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] Today, the arrondissement remains very dense in both population and business activity, with 71,962 jobs in the census of 1999.
[src:paris/10th-arrondissement-of-paris] Due to its large Turkish minority, the 10th arrondissement is often called "La Petite Turquie" (Little Turkey).
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The **11th arrondissement of Paris** (*XIe arrondissement*) is one of the 20 arrondissements of the capital city of France.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] In spoken French, the arrondissement is referred to as *le onzième* ([ɔ̃zjɛm]; "the eleventh").
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The arrondissement, called Popincourt, is situated on the right bank of the River Seine.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] It is one of the most densely populated urban districts of any European city.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] It is the best-served Parisian arrondissement in terms of number of Métro stations, at 25.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] Its borders are marked by three large squares: the Place de la République to the northwest, the Place de la Bastille to the southwest, as well as the Place de la Nation to the southeast.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The 11th arrondissement is a varied and engaging area.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] To the west lies the Place de la République, which is linked to the Place de la Bastille, in the east, by the sweeping, tree-lined Boulevard Richard-Lenoir, with its large markets and children's parks.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Place de la Bastille and the Rue du Faubourg Saint-Antoine are full of fashionable cafés, restaurants, as well as nightlife; they also contain a range of boutiques and galleries.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Oberkampf district to the north is another popular area for nightlife.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The east is more residential, with more wholesale commerce, while the areas around Boulevard Voltaire and Avenue Parmentier are livelier crossroads for the local community.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] In recent years this area has emerged as one of the trendiest parts of Paris.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] On 13 November 2015, the arrondissement was the site (among others) of coordinated Islamic shootings and bombings, particularly at the Bataclan theatre, which left 130 dead.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] About 20 years earlier, another attack had taken place.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The land area of this arrondissement is 3.666 km2 (1.415 sq mi; 906 acres).
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The peak population of Paris's 11th arrondissement occurred in 1911, with 242,295 inhabitants, and so, 66,020 inhabitants/km2.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] In 2023, the arrondissement remains the most densely populated in Paris with 37,690 inhabitants/km2, and the densest urban district in Europe.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] It is accompanied by a large volume of business activity: 83,870 jobs.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] The population consists of a large number of single adults, though its eastern portions are more family-oriented.
[src:paris/11th-arrondissement-of-paris] There is a strong community spirit in most areas of the eleventh, and it is interspersed with squares and parks.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The **12th arrondissement of Paris** (*XIIe arrondissement*) is one of the 20 arrondissements of the capital city of France.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Situated on the right bank of the River Seine, it is the easternmost arrondissement of Paris, as well as the largest by area.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The 12th arrondissement comprises the Gare de Lyon and Bois de Vincennes.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] It borders the inner suburbs of Charenton-le-Pont and Saint-Mandé in Val-de-Marne.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] It is in the 12th arrondissement that some of the oldest traces of human occupation of the territory now occupied by Paris were found.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] During the construction of Bercy Village in the 1980s, vestiges of a Neolithic village were discovered (dating from between 4500 and 3800 BC).
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Subsequent excavations turned up wooden canoes (the pirogues de Bercy), bows and arrows, pottery and bone and stone tools.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Some of these objects are now exhibited in the Carnavalet Museum.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] During the Roman era, the area that is now the 12th arrondissement was a largely uninhabited wetland fed by streams originating in the surrounding hills.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The area was crossed by a Roman road that linked Paris to Chelles and Meaux to the east and to Melun to the southeast.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] In the 11th century, the forest that would later become the bois de Vincennes was considered to be non-arable land.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] When Hugues Capet, King of the Franks, took up residence on the Île de la Cité, he used the bois de Vincennes as his hunting ground.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The bois was then reserved for the exclusive use of the kings of France.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] A hunting lodge was built by Louis VII around 1150, which was upgraded to a Manor House by Philippe Auguste, who made it a royal residence that was used over the 1150–1340 period.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Legend has it that Louis IX, Saint Louis, administered justice under an oak tree in what is now the bois de Vincennes.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The long process of turning this residence into a fortified castle, the Château de Vincennes, began in about 1337, when Philippe VI de Valois decided to build a dungeon near the Manor House.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Progressive upgrades by subsequent kings led to the construction of the fortifications, the Saint Chapelle de Vincennes and several residences within the fortified walls that were designed to cater to royal tastes and standards of living.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The last king to use the Château extensively as a royal residence was Louis XIV, who later abandoned it in favour of the Château de Versailles.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] In 1198, Foulques de Neuilly, preacher of the 4th crusade, built a small hermitage for reformed prostitutes in the marshes of what was to become the 12th arrondissement.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] In 1204, a Cistercian abbey, Saint Anthony of the Fields, was founded outside and to the east of the walls of Paris.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Abbaye was protected by fortified walls and a moat.:14.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Its church was dedicated to Saint Antoine, which gave the name, *Faubourg Saint Antoine* (Saint Anthony's suburb), to the neighbourhood that grew up around the Abbey.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Abbey housed nuns (*moniales*) and, quite quickly, became an institution dominated by noble women with direct connections to both the royal house and other major noble families.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Abbesse was referred to as the *Dame du Faubourg*.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Over several centuries, the Abbey benefited from the fact that these women were well integrated into the reigning economic and political power structures of Paris.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The *Faubourg* developed a specialty in furniture making and, especially, in cabinet making.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The development was due mainly to the protection and favours accorded by the kings of France to the Abbey and its dependents, including a dispensation from taxes for artisans working in the territory of the Abbey.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Starting in the 17th century, the Royal Mirror Manufacture was established in the *Faubourg* and further consolidated its reputation.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] This institution this would later become the multinational enterprise, Saint Gobain.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The distinctive courtyards and narrow passageways that characterise the *Faubourg* served groups of craftsmen who lived and worked together in the same building.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The resulting Viaduc des Arts provides workshops for a wide array of specialised crafts.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Nevertheless, most traces of the furniture-making activity in the *Faubourg* have disappeared, though the École Boule, a famous school for furniture design founded in 1886:51 and located in the 12th arrondissement, continues to bear witness to this ancient artisanal tradition.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The area next to the Seine that is now the 12th arrondissement was favoured by the French aristocracy as the site for their luxurious country estates.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] These included the "folie Rambouillet" which built by the Protestant financier and royal counsellor, Nicolas de Rambouillet, between 1633 and 1635.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The property was further developed by Madame de la Sablière (1636–1693), who received prominent non-Catholic ambassadors there prior to their formal entry into Paris.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] She also hosted elegant receptions and salons there and offered lodging to the poet, Jean de la Fontaine.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The estate was particularly known for its gardens, which were left open for the public to visit.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Another major estate was the 17th and 18th century Château de Bercy, which straddled the village of Charenton and the eastern part of the 12th arrondissement.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Its gardens were developed by the famous landscape architect, André le Notre.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Built on a promontory overlooking the Seine, the Chateau offered broad views over formal French gardens and the river.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Starting in 1804, the rapid development of the wine trade in the vicinity of the castle brought heavy river and road traffic and initiated what was to become a progressive abandonment of the property.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The château itself was destroyed in 1861.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The artisans and workers of the *Faubourg* played a key role in the French Revolution and the violent political turmoil of the 19th century.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Residents of the *Faubourg* were instrumental in the taking of the Bastille on 14 July 1789.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] There were only seven prisoners left in the Bastille at that point and the action cost the lives of 98 attackers as well as most of the rather small contingent of soldiers charged with defending it.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The unauthorised demolition of the Bastille began the day after the Bastille was taken when an entrepreneurial business man, Pierre-François Palloy, recruited a team to tear down the fortress.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The neighbourhood also played a prominent role in the Reign of Terror that followed.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] In the southern part of what is now the Place de la Nation, a guillotine was erected in June 1794.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Of the 2,639 people guillotined in Paris during the Revolution, 1,306 were beheaded there.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Their bodies were then thrown into two mass graves in what is now the nearby Picpus Cemetery.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] After the Revolution, the Faubourg remained a hotbed of revolutionary activity, including during the July Revolution, the 1848 Revolution and the Paris Commune.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] From 1815 onwards, the neighbourhoods that would later become the 12th arrondissement were the focus of far-reaching urban development projects.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] These include construction of: the July Column (Colonne de Juillet) on the Place de la Bastille (1830); the Halle Beauvau (the covered market on the Rue d'Aligre, 1843); the mainline Gare de Lyon (1847–1852) and the Paris-Vincennes rail line that terminated at the Gare de la Bastille (1855).
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Haussmann was also active in this sector, creating arteries that would later take the names of boulevard Diderot (1854), rue Chaligny (1856), avenue Daumesnil (1859) and rue Crozatier (1861).
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Between 1855 and 1866, the Bois de Vincennes was refurbished by order of Napoleon III, who wanted it to become a "vast park for the working populations of eastern Paris".
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] La Place de la Nation received its current name on 14 July 1880.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Prior to that date, it was called the place du Trône, in honour of the entry into Paris of Louis XIV and his new wife, Marie-Thérèse of Austria.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Le columns and associated taxation offices that can still be seen on the eastern portion of the place, were part of a much broader set of some 60 tax barriers surrounding Paris that were designed by the architect, Claude Ledoux.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Built in 1787, tax officials were stationed there to collect revenues from people as they entered Paris with their merchandise.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] During the reign of Louis-Philippe (1830–1848), the statues of two French kings were placed on the tops of the two columns: Saint Louis (Louis IX) is on the 11th arrondissement side and Philippe Auguste on the 12th arrondissement side.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The sculpture that dominates the central part of the Place, Jules Dalou's *Le Triomphe de la République*, was originally a contender, but not the winner, of a competition for a sculpture to be erected on the Place de la République.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] However, in 1880, responding to popular demand, the municipal council decided to order the statue for the Place de la Nation.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] From an administrative point of view, the present-day 12th arrondissement was created by law of 16 June 1859, which rearranged Paris into the 20 arrondissements known today.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The law also extended the arrondissement by absorbing parts of the villages of Bercy (including the wine warehouses of Bercy) and Saint-Mandé.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The first town hall, located to the southeast of the current town hall, was burned down by the Commune.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The current town hall was built in 1876 on Avenue Daumesnil, following the plans of architect Antoine-Julien Hénard.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Bois de Vincennes was given to the City of Paris by Emperor Napoleon III in 1860, but was not officially integrated into the 12th arrondissement until 1926.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The arrondissement benefited from numerous urban renewal and public works projects, many of them initiated during the 1980s.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Two of the eight 'Grands Projets of Francois Mitterrand' that were the hallmark of his presidency were located in the 12th arrondissement.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] These were the Opéra de la Bastille and the Ministry of the Economy and Finance building.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Major projects in the eastern section of the arrondissement include the French Ministry of Finances, Bercy Village, the Parc de Bercy and the Bercy arena, now renamed Accorhotels Arena.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Farther to the west, the arrondissement also features the Opéra de la Bastille, the second largest opera house in Paris.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] It was inaugurated by Francois Mitterrand in 1989, on the 200th anniversary of the storming of the Bastille.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Coulée verte René-Dumont (or Promenade plantée) was developed at the same time as the Opéra de la Bastille.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] It is a 4.7 km (2.9 mi) elevated linear park built on top of obsolete railway infrastructure.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The Viaduc des Arts, a string of workshops for skilled artisans, is also part of this development.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] It is located at the base of the western part of the Coulée verte René-Dumont.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Like most neighbourhoods in Paris, the 12th arrondissement offers a rich array of historically important and aesthetically appealing sites.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] For the 12th, these sites emerged mainly from development during the 19th century and from the late 20th century urban renewal projects.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The land area of this arrondissement is 16.324 km2 (6.303 sq mi; 4,034 acres), two-thirds of which consists of the Bois de Vincennes park.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] Excluding the Bois de Vincennes, its land area is 6.377 km2 (2.462 sq mi; 1,576 acres).
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] The peak of population of Paris's 12th arrondissement occurred in 1962 and was followed by three decades of decline.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] More recently, however, the population has begun to grow again, especially since the urban renewal projects of the 1990s.
[src:paris/12th-arrondissement-of-paris] However, after 2012 the population showed a slight decline.
